<br>
This blatancy just goes unnoticed most of the time.  For every Gay Pride Parade, there are thousands of celebrations of heterosexuality, ranging from weddings to television shows to movies (and even TV shows and movies about weddings).<br>
<br>
David, your argument is fundamentally flawed.  The &quot;closet&quot; is the worst trap for any lesbian, gay man, bisexual, or transgender person, and it's the worst trap for the movement as a whole.  It allows heterosexual privilege to remain uncontested and, largely, invisible.  The Pride Parades are periods when that privilege is most clearly visible.<br>
<br>
Listen to your own rhetoric for a moment, then take a look around you.  What you appear to resent is queer visibility.  Well, why shouldn't queers resent heterosexual visibility?  Most of us don't, in fact, resent it except when people make disingenuous arguments like the one you're making here.<br>
<br>
Also, you contradict yourself so many times throughout this sequence of posts, my head is spinning.  Let me start with Sartre, though.  You quoted his oft-cited &quot;existence precedes essence&quot;.  That's all well and good, but then you say you could never find yourself attracted to another man.  That's pretty essentialist, don't you think?  (It also indicates you have no idea what &quot;existence precedes essence&quot; means.  I do, so be careful here.  Querying &quot;essentialism&quot; in all its forms is one of the things I do best.)<br>
<br>
Also, you construct a &quot;good queer/bad queer&quot; dichotomy in some of your posts: &quot;if only they'd act normal, they'd get acceptance.&quot;  Historical experience, as well as my own personal experience, has shown me this is untrue.  No one ever gained any rights being silent.<br>
<br>
Lastly (and although I recognize these to be a pair of blows below the belt, I'm going to make them anyway), what makes you think you have any standing at all to speak on what rhetorical strategies gay men, lesbians, bisexuals, and transgender people should be using?  You certainly disavow any membership in the affected communities (and, in fact, your membership in *THIS* community that we're speaking in now is somewhat suspect--some could argue you sold those rights out along with your character).  Are you arrogantly and presumptuously telling queers what's good for them? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/LASLAN.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->andersonrob@earthlink.net<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/index.html<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->EverQuest: Lasgalen Lothir, Firiona Vie server</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=robingoodfellow>Robin Goodfellow</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/RAINBO~1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1122<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/14/03 4:33:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=294.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oral Sex Pride Parade!!!! </span><hr size=1> Okay, I need to do a few follow-up things.<br>
<br>
David, you said you &quot;choose&quot; to be attracted to females.<br>
<br>
Really?  You mean it's like a switch, and you could equally &quot;choose&quot; to be attracted to males?  It's just that easy for you?<br>
<br>
Was there a time in your life when you were attracted to men, but made a conscious decision to be only attracted to women?<br>
<br>
Okay, then, here's a challenge for you.  Spend a week being attracted to men.  Just one week.<br>
<br>
Second, I'm deeply, deeply disturbed by the suggestion that the problem is difference itself, not the hatred of difference, and that the solution is the erasure of that difference.  It doesn't take much of a logical leap to get from that to the fascist &quot;Final Solution&quot; to the &quot;Jewish Problem&quot; (or the &quot;Homosexual Problem&quot;, for that matter)--in fact, that was the logical step taken by the Nazis (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>pace</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Godwin's Law).<br>
<br>
The obliteration of difference cannot be accomplished without obliterating those who are different, either by forcing them to assimilate to the &quot;norm&quot; (and thereby eliminating their difference, and virtually eliminating them) or by literally oblitering them.<br>
<br>
It's sad that people are so frightened by others' difference, but that should no more excuse homophobia than it excuses racism.<br>
<br>
This is a rhetorical strategy I've seen more and more of in the last ten years, spawned primarily by those calling themselves &quot;libertarian&quot; (primarily white, middle class, and male, mind you) and billed as the solution to all the nation's social ills, ranging from racism to homophobia.  We've come to believe that racism doesn't exist anymore, that homophobia doesn't exist anymore, that sexism doesn't exist anymore, and therefore the need to organize politically around identity is &quot;counterproductive&quot;.  This is either an extremely naive position, as oppression based on race, sex, and sexual orientation certainly continue to manifest in our nation, or it's an extremely cynical one.  More and more, I'm coming to believe it's a cynical one, most often articulated by those who are in power in order to disempower those they oppress.  Since it alleviates the guilty consciences of many in privileged classes, it's a surprisingly effective strategy. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jullietstarshooter>julliet starshooter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/14/03 5:04:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=294.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oral Sex Pride Parade!!!! </span><hr size=1> You know...I once knew a man who was the nicest guy in the world. He treated me with kindness, dignity, and respect. He was educated and had a career. He would have made the perfect husband/father for some lucky woman. I was fortunate enough to know this man...but whatever I did...I JUST COULD NOT FALL IN LOVE WITH HIM! I WAS NOT ATTRACTED TO HIM AND NOTHING I DID OR HE DID COULD CHANGE THAT!<br>
