<br>
But I think both views on difference are correct... one or the other won't work.  I think most hatred stems from the idea that another group of people are &quot;other&quot; as opposed to &quot;us&quot;; it's a very primal concept.  My tribe good, their tribe not good.  As long as people continue to view gays, blacks, Jews, or what have you as the &quot;other&quot; there will be problems.  This is why I think television can be one of the most powerful tools for reducing bigotry.  If you show a person who is currently considered in the &quot;other&quot; category doing something that is usually constrained to &quot;us&quot;, you have made a step towards making that person an &quot;us.&quot;  Note that this does not require changing the person to be more like an &quot;us&quot;; it only requires that they be put in a normal position.  For example Will on Will and Grace... he's a normal lawyer.  He's gay, certainly, but he's filling a roll that would generally be considered more of a straight roll.  Or, more notably, luetenent (sp) Ohura on Star Trek.  How many people realized, that in a time when segregation was still a bit more promenient than it is today, a black woman was 4th in command on that show?  They didn't try to make her more like a white woman, she was just black, and 4th in command.<br>
<br>
Thus, it is not removal of difference which removes the &quot;other&quot; instinct, but rather simply showing someone who has a difference as being &quot;us&quot; as well.  I think this is the strategy you're thinking about David.<br>
<br>
But all this does not mean silence is a virtue.  If people attempt to hide, and simply blend in, nothing is solved.  Ohura made a subtle difference to our culture because she was clearly a black woman... and she was in an important role.<br>
<br>
Thus, if people can openly be gay, celebrate being gay, and make that part of our culture, make that part of being an &quot;us&quot;, then and only then have they won equality, only then can a person declair themselves to be gay without instantly becoming an &quot;other.&quot;  <br>
<br>
I'd write this more clearly, but I just woke up and have to go to work.<br>
<br>
Jarkell Ravensteel <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vampiricmuse>Vampiric Muse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blood is sexah ;)</span><br>  Posts: 120<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/14/03 2:13:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=294.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://eqsighost.netfirms.com/DavidStrange/vamp.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Oral Sex Pride Parade!!!! </span><hr size=1> I was late for physics class so I did not get the give proper attention to the &quot;choice&quot; theory I had.  Will do so now.  As for your point I will say that I do know that racism, homophobia, and all that happen.  I am simply trying to find a method to fix that.  Whether my theory would work or not we will probabaly never know.  Just my opinion.  But now to the &quot;choice&quot; theory I have.<br>
<br>
We all have preferences.  This is where most people say sexual identity revolves.  Someone may have a preference for males or females, or preference for a specific type of food.  My theory is that while we have these preferences, it has been our experiences that form these preferences.  To counteract a specific preference to allow yourself to make a &quot;choice&quot; about one, all that is needed is for you to allow yourself the oppurtunity to experience things outside of your preference.  To start let's take an easy one, food.  My fiancee and I got together 4 years ago.  When we met she would not spice any of her food as all of her life she had eaten food that was not spicy.  It was her preference not to eat spicy food.  I on the other hand love spicy food and talked her into trying some of my cooking.  She now has the preference for spicy food that she never had before due to having new experiences.<br>
<br>
Where I am going with this is that everyday children, young adults, and adults are living in a heterosexual world (see we do not disagree on this.  I do believe there is sexual discrimination).  When we are kids we see our parents (most often heterosexual), we see couples (most often heterosexual), and we are influenced by these.  It is no wonder that the majority of people have a heterosexual preference.  However, if one of these people were to strip their notions of homosexuality being &quot;wrong&quot;, &quot;gross&quot;, or whatever they have and truly be open to a homosexual experience then they would have the choice as to which preference they preferred.  If they loved the sex in a same-sex relationship, or if they love the companionship they get in it, or if they just decide that the same sex is more attractive, for me it is still a choice to open up and decide.<br>
<br>
The problem lies with the people who have the homosexual experiences but do not strip their notions of the &quot;immorality or grossness&quot; of the experience that society has imparted to them.  These people make up the ashamed homosexual community.  I truly feel sorry for people who can not respect what they are.<br>
<br>
I hope this illustrates my point better Robin.  I don't see myself as a homophobe and hope that you don't either.  I try to keep an open mind to everything I encounter and judge only when necessary.<br>
<br>
As for your challenge, maybe if I did not have a fiancee, but to do so would ruin both of our lives. <p>David Strange<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
